why doesn't it give error just like we get in java code?

Android does not have a strict error checking mechanism for XML files. It uses a different parser to parse the XML files and assigns IDs to the views. If you have the same IDs in different XML files, the parser will simply assign the same ID to the views in the second XML file. This is why you don't get an error.

how does environment decide to which component it needs to invoke?

The environment uses the IDs assigned to the views in the XML files. When you call findViewById(), you pass the ID of the view you want to retrieve. The environment then uses this ID to find the corresponding view in the current view hierarchy.

What will happen in such case?

If you set the same XML layout as the content view for an Activity, both layouts will be part of the view hierarchy. You can then use findViewById() to get references to the views in either layout.

How to switch xml layout ordering:

You can achieve this by conditionally setting the content view based on a certain condition. If the condition is met, you set the layout with the "ylist" appearing first. If the condition is not met, you set the original layout.

Please using this api: Activity.setContentView.

You can use Activity.setContentView() to set the layout for your Activity. This method should be called from your Activity's onCreate() method. The layout parameter should be the ID of your layout resource.

Answer:

You can use Activity.setContentView() to set the layout for your Activity. This method should be called from your Activity's onCreate() method. The layout parameter should be the ID of your layout resource.

Here is an example:

```java
@Override
public void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    if(condition){
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main_ylist_first);
    }else{
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);
    }
    ListView xlist = (ListView) findViewById(R.id.xlist);
    ListView ylist = (ListView) findViewById(R.id.ylist);
}
```

In this example, if the condition is true, the layout with the "ylist" appearing first will be set. If the condition is false, the original layout will be set.

Please note that the IDs in the layouts should be unique. If they are not, the parser will simply assign the same ID to the views in the second layout.

